Universal programs means that nobody is left behind, this prevents the government from making silly excuses to cut important programs for the people.

snippet.textDisplay:
What economy started off as a socialist economy and prosper? It was capitalism that pulled billions of people out of poverty. And now socialists want to spit on capitalism that took them out of poverty. And when I say poverty, I don't mean having to take the bus, I mean not having food to eat even though you're starving. Socialists have been enjoying the wealth generating effect of capitalism, whether directly or indirectly, but are now hypocritically blaming capitalism. You may hate rich people, but you're the one that made them rich by buying their things. Some rich people do lobby the government to make rules that favor them, and that's wrong, but the government is also to be blamed for being corrupt. But capitalism is not the enemy. Greedy people is the enemy, and regardless what economic model you choose, there will always be bad and greedy people even in the government. When socialists make the government bigger, give them more power, and more control over your education, your healthcare, your retirement, more greedy people will infiltrate the government and hold power over you. They will secretly funnel the wealth to them, their family, and friends. The quality of your education will go down, the quality of your healthcare will go down, and your retirement money may just be numbers on a paper that doesn't actually exist. Cities have gone bankrupt because they can't pay out the pension they promised, and people retired with pension that couldn't pay.


Inviting big government into your lives is just suicidal. Work, save, and manage your own wealth. Don't give 60% or higher of your hard earned money to the government, because you will not get back that amount. As a millennial, I very much disliked paying social security taxes knowing full well when I retire, I'll only get back a fraction of it, if any. I much rather put that Social Security tax into a Roth IRA or 401K where I am the account owner, and no one can legally dip into it but me.

snippet.textDisplay: There's no perfect solution, but wealth taxation hasn't worked elsewhere and it stands to reason that it wouldn't in the US.  1) wealth tax hit incomes (but the rich will find loopholes in this in tax laws) 2) Psychologically speaking, who wants to make more, if you get taxed more (this goes to argument #1, but also moving your corporation overseas or Puerto Rico).  It sounds good in theory, but I don't believe it works in practice.  That and where will the money EXACTLY go is the question. Best case, it's a watered-down version of what may happen and/or doesn't help the everyday citizen.
